WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.680 --> 00:00:04.190
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, D.C.

00:00:04.190 --> 00:00:11.870
&gt;&gt; We have our next author
coming up to the stage.

00:00:11.870 --> 00:00:13.570
And his name is Chris Van Dusen.

00:00:13.570 --> 00:00:15.660
He's an author and an illustrator.

00:00:15.660 --> 00:00:21.830
And when Chris Van Dusen was a
kid, he drew and drew and drew.

00:00:21.830 --> 00:00:27.580
He especially liked to draw things
like aliens, robots, and monsters.

00:00:27.580 --> 00:00:30.050
Two of his childhood heroes
were authors and illustrators

00:00:30.050 --> 00:00:34.060
of children's books: Dr.
Seuss and Robert McCloskey.

00:00:34.060 --> 00:00:37.550
Little did Chris know that one day
he, himself, would be an author

00:00:37.550 --> 00:00:39.280
and an illustrator of
many children's books.

00:00:39.280 --> 00:00:41.480
You might recognize his artwork

00:00:41.480 --> 00:00:44.190
from the incredibly
popular Mercy Watson series.

00:00:44.190 --> 00:00:48.240
He's here today to talk about
his new book, Hattie and Hudson,

00:00:48.240 --> 00:00:51.580
a story about the unlikely
friendship between a little girl

00:00:51.580 --> 00:00:56.350
and one of Mr. Van Dusen's
childhood specialties, a monster.

00:00:56.350 --> 00:01:01.010
He will sign copies of his new
book from 11:30 to 12:30 PM

00:01:01.010 --> 00:01:02.780
over there, in that direction.

00:01:02.780 --> 00:01:06.510
Please make some noise
for Chris Van Dusen.

00:01:06.510 --> 00:01:19.270
[ Applause ]

00:01:19.270 --> 00:01:20.570
&gt;&gt; Chris Van Dusen: Hi, guys.

00:01:20.570 --> 00:01:21.960
How are you?

00:01:21.960 --> 00:01:24.010
Thanks for coming today.

00:01:24.010 --> 00:01:26.900
I am so excited to
be -- oh, thank you.

00:01:26.900 --> 00:01:30.140
That'd be good since I left
mine back at the hotel.

00:01:30.140 --> 00:01:35.930
I'm going to set these -- I guess
I can put those right there.

00:01:35.930 --> 00:01:37.340
Well, good morning, everybody.

00:01:37.340 --> 00:01:38.640
Thanks for coming out today.

00:01:38.640 --> 00:01:39.940
This is great!

00:01:39.940 --> 00:01:41.240
I like the bean-bag idea.

00:01:41.240 --> 00:01:44.280
It's kind of like a child
mosh-pit-type thing.

00:01:44.280 --> 00:01:46.750
Isn't it? I like that a lot.

00:01:46.750 --> 00:01:48.520
My name is Chris.

00:01:48.520 --> 00:01:50.110
I live in Maine.

00:01:50.110 --> 00:01:53.770
And I'm going to start, actually,
kind of go off script here

00:01:53.770 --> 00:01:57.060
and I would feel bad if I
didn't sort of give a shout-out

00:01:57.060 --> 00:01:58.750 position:56%
to the people in Texas who are going

00:01:58.750 --> 00:02:01.510
through this horrible
time, as you all know.

00:02:01.510 --> 00:02:03.830
I mean just seeing
the things on the TV.

00:02:03.830 --> 00:02:06.400
All the amount of rain
those people are having.

00:02:06.400 --> 00:02:07.700
It's just unbelievable.

00:02:07.700 --> 00:02:11.070
Up in Maine, what we do
is a lot of times we sort

00:02:11.070 --> 00:02:13.810
of convert rain amounts
to snow amounts.

00:02:13.810 --> 00:02:17.100
And it turns out to be
approximately like one inch

00:02:17.100 --> 00:02:19.390
of rain equals a foot of snow.

00:02:19.390 --> 00:02:23.440
So if Harvey had come to Maine and
sort of churned around the Gulf

00:02:23.440 --> 00:02:27.060
of Maine for a week, like it
did off the coast of Texas,

00:02:27.060 --> 00:02:31.710
we would have had about 48
feet of snow in our town.

00:02:31.710 --> 00:02:34.280
And all you would see
is a big pile of snow

00:02:34.280 --> 00:02:36.330
with a church steeple
sticking up because I live

00:02:36.330 --> 00:02:38.430
in a little town on
the coast of Maine.

00:02:38.430 --> 00:02:40.660
But that just seems
so absurd, right?

00:02:40.660 --> 00:02:43.940
And it's because the
amount of rain they got

00:02:43.940 --> 00:02:45.770
down there was just unbelievable.

00:02:45.770 --> 00:02:48.770
So I hope the recovery goes well.

00:02:48.770 --> 00:02:50.410
I really feel bad for those people.

00:02:50.410 --> 00:02:55.710
Before I left Maine yesterday, I
heard on the news that in Portland,

00:02:55.710 --> 00:02:57.260
which is the largest city in Maine,

00:02:57.260 --> 00:03:00.790 position:56%
they put a great big tractor-trailer
truck right in the middle

00:03:00.790 --> 00:03:02.590
of Monument Square, which is
right in the middle of the city,

00:03:02.590 --> 00:03:04.750
and they just opened up the
back, because it was empty,

00:03:04.750 --> 00:03:07.690
and they just encouraged people
to come and just put stuff

00:03:07.690 --> 00:03:10.250
in the tractor trailer
for the people of Texas.

00:03:10.250 --> 00:03:13.950
So I hope by now that that
truck is pretty well filled up.

00:03:13.950 --> 00:03:15.250
All right.

00:03:15.250 --> 00:03:16.550
So let's talk about books.

00:03:16.550 --> 00:03:17.850
That's why we're here.

00:03:17.850 --> 00:03:21.200
Right? So I'm an author/illustrator
of children's picture books.

00:03:21.200 --> 00:03:22.500
You guys may know that.

00:03:22.500 --> 00:03:26.120
I actually started my career
by being an illustrator.

00:03:26.120 --> 00:03:28.340
Do you -- all you kids
know what an illustrator --

00:03:28.340 --> 00:03:30.080
who can raise their hand and
tell me what an illustrator does?

00:03:30.080 --> 00:03:31.580
What does an illustrator do?

00:03:31.580 --> 00:03:35.430
[Inaudible] That's right:
someone who draws pictures.

00:03:35.430 --> 00:03:38.210
It's really just kind of a
fancy name for someone who gets

00:03:38.210 --> 00:03:41.370
to stay home and draw pictures all
day long, because that's what I do.

00:03:41.370 --> 00:03:44.460
I stay home, at home,
and I just draw pictures,

00:03:44.460 --> 00:03:47.200
usually in my slippers, and I
just draw pictures all day long.

00:03:47.200 --> 00:03:49.620
I get to draw the coolest pictures.

00:03:49.620 --> 00:03:53.240
But I didn't start writing books
until quite a few years later.

00:03:53.240 --> 00:03:54.920
So I started out as an illustrator

00:03:54.920 --> 00:03:57.460
and then years later I
started doing the writing.

00:03:57.460 --> 00:04:01.820
And I did a lot of illustrations
for all sorts of magazines.

00:04:01.820 --> 00:04:03.970
That's what most of my
work was: for magazines.

00:04:03.970 --> 00:04:07.360
And I noticed the type of magazines
I really loved illustrating

00:04:07.360 --> 00:04:09.450
for were kids' magazines,

00:04:09.450 --> 00:04:11.960
because those are the magazines
I could do these crazy,

00:04:11.960 --> 00:04:13.530
outlandish illustrations.

00:04:13.530 --> 00:04:15.890
Kind of cartoony, which
is what I like.

00:04:15.890 --> 00:04:18.330
And I just loved illustrating
for the kids' magazines.

00:04:18.330 --> 00:04:23.310 position:56%
Well, one day I was in my studio and
I was working on an illustration,

00:04:23.310 --> 00:04:26.470
and this image popped into my head.

00:04:26.470 --> 00:04:28.650
And I don't know why
this popped in my head,

00:04:28.650 --> 00:04:32.670
but it was a very vivid
image that had to come out.

00:04:32.670 --> 00:04:36.280
And the picture that I
pictured in my head was of a man

00:04:36.280 --> 00:04:40.110
in a little motorboat with his dog

00:04:40.110 --> 00:04:43.200
and they were stuck way
up in the top of a tree.

00:04:43.200 --> 00:04:46.500
And I don't know why that popped
in my head, but I thought,

00:04:46.500 --> 00:04:48.980
"That would be really fun to draw."

00:04:48.980 --> 00:04:52.470
And so I grabbed a scrap of paper
and I quickly drew this little man

00:04:52.470 --> 00:04:54.460
in his boat on the top of a tree.

00:04:54.460 --> 00:04:56.630
And I set it aside and
I went back to work.

00:04:56.630 --> 00:04:58.110
So I'm working away
on my illustration.

00:04:58.110 --> 00:05:00.040
I kept looking over
at that illustration,

00:05:00.040 --> 00:05:03.210
that little sketch
I did and I thought,

00:05:03.210 --> 00:05:05.940 position:56%
"I want to know more about that man.

00:05:05.940 --> 00:05:09.470
I want to know more about who he
is, how he ended up in the top

00:05:09.470 --> 00:05:13.520
of the tree, how he got there,
how is he going to get down?"

00:05:13.520 --> 00:05:18.770
And so for the next few hours, the
next few days, the next few weeks,

00:05:18.770 --> 00:05:24.480
I thought about that little picture
that I did, and nine years later,

00:05:24.480 --> 00:05:28.680
that little sketch evolved into
my first book which was called

00:05:28.680 --> 00:05:30.200
Down to the Sea with Mr. Magee.

00:05:30.200 --> 00:05:31.500
Has anybody ever seen that book?

00:05:31.500 --> 00:05:33.360
Some of you guys have seen that?

00:05:33.360 --> 00:05:34.660
Oh, awesome!

00:05:34.660 --> 00:05:35.960
I didn't think anybody outside

00:05:35.960 --> 00:05:38.320
of Maine had heard of
that book actually.

00:05:38.320 --> 00:05:39.690
But anyway, that was my first book.

00:05:39.690 --> 00:05:41.990
When it came out I wasn't sure
I was going to do another book.

00:05:41.990 --> 00:05:44.260
I wasn't sure if it
was going to be a dud

00:05:44.260 --> 00:05:47.110
or if people were going
to actually like it.

00:05:47.110 --> 00:05:50.030
And so I went back to doing
magazine illustration.

00:05:50.030 --> 00:05:52.840
But I guess it did well enough
because the publisher asked me

00:05:52.840 --> 00:05:54.820
if I'd like to do another
Mr. Magee book.

00:05:54.820 --> 00:05:59.110
And so I wrote a book about
Mr. Magee going camping

00:05:59.110 --> 00:06:01.620
and that's called A Camping
Spree with Mr. Magee.

00:06:01.620 --> 00:06:03.320
Has anybody seen --
you seen that one?

00:06:03.320 --> 00:06:05.920
Yeah? Okay.

00:06:05.920 --> 00:06:09.250
Wow. That -- see I -- that
kind of blows me away.

00:06:09.250 --> 00:06:11.940
I just didn't know you guys
would know those books.

00:06:11.940 --> 00:06:14.430
Because I'm probably best known,

00:06:14.430 --> 00:06:18.810
one of my best-known books is
a book called The Circus Ship.

00:06:18.810 --> 00:06:22.060
You guys seen this one?

00:06:22.060 --> 00:06:25.570
[Applause] So The Circus Ship
came out in 2009, it was published

00:06:25.570 --> 00:06:30.450
by Candlewick Press, and it was
loosely based on a true story.

00:06:30.450 --> 00:06:33.660 position:56%
Off the coast of Maine where I live,
and I live about mid-coast Maine,

00:06:33.660 --> 00:06:34.960
there were two big islands.

00:06:34.960 --> 00:06:37.470
One's called Vinalhaven;
one's called North Haven.

00:06:37.470 --> 00:06:44.980 position:56%
And there really was a ship carrying
a circus in 1836 that sank --

00:06:44.980 --> 00:06:47.690
Circus Ship, love it --
off the coast of Maine.

00:06:47.690 --> 00:06:49.680
Right off the coast
from where I live.

00:06:49.680 --> 00:06:54.410
And I read about it in a magazine,
and it really fascinated me

00:06:54.410 --> 00:06:57.990
that there was an elephant swimming

00:06:57.990 --> 00:07:01.380
around in Penobscot Bay
about 175 years ago.

00:07:01.380 --> 00:07:04.040
And that's right --
that's where our harbor

00:07:04.040 --> 00:07:06.610
in our town is, right
on Penobscot Bay.

00:07:06.610 --> 00:07:09.090
And I thought, "That is so cool."

00:07:09.090 --> 00:07:11.440
So I kind of logged it in
the back of my head somewhere

00:07:11.440 --> 00:07:14.200
because I wasn't -- even at that
point I wasn't even writing books.

00:07:14.200 --> 00:07:16.680
But eventually it sort
of popped back out

00:07:16.680 --> 00:07:18.490
and that became The Circus Ship.

00:07:18.490 --> 00:07:23.620
But I have to be honest,
I'm probably best-known

00:07:23.620 --> 00:07:28.980 position:56%
for being an illustrator of a series
of books about a little pig --

00:07:28.980 --> 00:07:31.540
or not a little pig
actually a pretty big pig --

00:07:31.540 --> 00:07:36.890
that causes a lot of havoc in a
neighborhood called Deckawoo Drive.

00:07:36.890 --> 00:07:39.690
And those are called
the Mercy Watson books.

00:07:39.690 --> 00:07:42.980 position:56%
Anybody seen the Mercy Watson books?

00:07:42.980 --> 00:07:47.780
[Cheering] Alright, now, I can only
claim the visual part of this book

00:07:47.780 --> 00:07:50.350
because as you guys probably
know, this is written

00:07:50.350 --> 00:07:53.120
by the amazing Kate
DiCamillo who's out here.

00:07:53.120 --> 00:07:56.750
And I'm basically the warm-up act
for Kate because she comes on next.

00:07:56.750 --> 00:08:00.860
So I'll get you guys
all prepped for Kate.

00:08:00.860 --> 00:08:02.230
But yeah, those were great.

00:08:02.230 --> 00:08:06.350 position:56%
These were really fun to illustrate.

00:08:06.350 --> 00:08:09.630
And the way these came about
is kind of a funny story.

00:08:09.630 --> 00:08:12.960
The art director at Candlewick
Press, her name is Ann Stott,

00:08:12.960 --> 00:08:16.450
that's the art director I work
with, she had my first three books.

00:08:16.450 --> 00:08:20.120
She had the Down to the Sea with
Mr. Magee, she had A Camping Spree

00:08:20.120 --> 00:08:23.940
with Mr. Magee and my third book
was a book called If I Built a Car.

00:08:23.940 --> 00:08:25.860
So she had all those.

00:08:25.860 --> 00:08:28.370
Thank you, I like a little
shout-out for -- that's great.

00:08:28.370 --> 00:08:32.830
So she had those books and what she
would do, and I didn't know this

00:08:32.830 --> 00:08:37.240 position:56%
until years later, but she would go
to the editorial meetings and that's

00:08:37.240 --> 00:08:40.410
where the editors and the art
directors get together and they try

00:08:40.410 --> 00:08:43.220
to figure out what illustrators are
going to illustrate these books.

00:08:43.220 --> 00:08:45.480
So she would come into the
meetings with the Mr. Magees

00:08:45.480 --> 00:08:49.250 position:56%
and If I Built a Car and she really
wanted to work with me on a project.

00:08:49.250 --> 00:08:55.200 position:56%
So they'd present some story or some
manuscript and Ann would say "Well,

00:08:55.200 --> 00:08:56.500
how about Chris for this?"

00:08:56.500 --> 00:08:58.460
And they'd say "No,
he's not quite right."

00:08:58.460 --> 00:09:01.430 position:56%
So the next manuscript would come,
she says "How about Chris for this?"

00:09:01.430 --> 00:09:03.260
"No, that's not quite right."

00:09:03.260 --> 00:09:06.400
Well, finally, I guess this
went on for weeks, months,

00:09:06.400 --> 00:09:09.290
and finally the manuscript
came in from Kate DiCamillo

00:09:09.290 --> 00:09:12.380
and it was called Mercy
Watson to the Rescue.

00:09:12.380 --> 00:09:14.430
And Ann tried one more time,

00:09:14.430 --> 00:09:17.190
she said "How about
Chris for these series?"

00:09:17.190 --> 00:09:20.220
And I think really she
just kind of wore them out.

00:09:20.220 --> 00:09:23.070
I think she just wanted them -- you
know, they just wanted her to shut

00:09:23.070 --> 00:09:24.370
up about Chris Van Dusen.

00:09:24.370 --> 00:09:27.620
So they said "okay, we'll
give Chris Van Dusen a shot."

00:09:27.620 --> 00:09:35.460
And so I got a call from an art
director I had never heard of,

00:09:35.460 --> 00:09:38.560
from a publisher I never
worked for, and said "would you

00:09:38.560 --> 00:09:41.030
like to illustrate a series
of books by Kate DiCamillo?"

00:09:41.030 --> 00:09:47.180 position:56%
And it was kind of like someone just
came to my door riding a unicorn

00:09:47.180 --> 00:09:48.940
with a pot of gold basically.

00:09:48.940 --> 00:09:50.240
Because that's what it felt.

00:09:50.240 --> 00:09:51.540
It felt so magical.

00:09:51.540 --> 00:09:54.730
And so for the next four years
of my life, and this is what it's

00:09:54.730 --> 00:09:56.030
like being an illustrator.

00:09:56.030 --> 00:09:57.890
You get a call one day
and someone says "Hey,

00:09:57.890 --> 00:09:59.190
how about for the next four years

00:09:59.190 --> 00:10:01.680
of your life you paint
nothing but pig pictures?

00:10:01.680 --> 00:10:03.500
Sometimes they're in pink dresses."

00:10:03.500 --> 00:10:05.340
And you go, "I'm your man.

00:10:05.340 --> 00:10:06.640
Sign me up."

00:10:06.640 --> 00:10:07.940
And so that's what I did
for the next four years,

00:10:07.940 --> 00:10:10.690
I did pig pictures
for the Mercy Watson.

00:10:10.690 --> 00:10:13.670
By the way, there are about
50 illustrations in each one

00:10:13.670 --> 00:10:17.000
of these books and there are six
books in the original series.

00:10:17.000 --> 00:10:18.910
So that's about 300 paintings,

00:10:18.910 --> 00:10:20.780
that's why it took
me about four years.

00:10:20.780 --> 00:10:25.320 position:56%
So. But the book we're talking about
today, and I haven't even gotten

00:10:25.320 --> 00:10:26.620
to it yet, is my latest book.

00:10:26.620 --> 00:10:27.920
It's called Hattie and Hudson.

00:10:27.920 --> 00:10:30.330
Has anybody seen this book yet?

00:10:30.330 --> 00:10:31.630
Some of you guys have?

00:10:31.630 --> 00:10:32.930
Oh, excellent.

00:10:32.930 --> 00:10:38.040
So this came out in May
and it's a different book

00:10:38.040 --> 00:10:41.240
for me for two main reasons.

00:10:41.240 --> 00:10:44.980
The first reason is,
it's not a rhyming story.

00:10:44.980 --> 00:10:47.900
All the books I've written up to
this point are rhyming stories.

00:10:47.900 --> 00:10:50.680
I mean, the Mercy Watsons
aren't but I didn't write those.

00:10:50.680 --> 00:10:55.490
But The Circus Ship and the Mr.
Magee books, the If I Built books,

00:10:55.490 --> 00:10:59.620
King Hugo's Huge Ego, Randy
Riley's Really Big Hit,

00:10:59.620 --> 00:11:01.090
they're all rhyming books.

00:11:01.090 --> 00:11:02.910
If I Built a House.

00:11:02.910 --> 00:11:06.230
And so this is the first
time I've written a book

00:11:06.230 --> 00:11:08.050
in prose instead of verse.

00:11:08.050 --> 00:11:10.160
It's also the first
book I've written

00:11:10.160 --> 00:11:13.220
where a girl is the main character.

00:11:13.220 --> 00:11:15.060
Right, girls?

00:11:15.060 --> 00:11:16.850
[Cheering] Little fist
pump for girls.

00:11:16.850 --> 00:11:21.220
And the reason I did this because
I go around to schools mostly

00:11:21.220 --> 00:11:23.990
up in Maine where I live
and I talk to the kids.

00:11:23.990 --> 00:11:25.290
And a lot of kids were starting

00:11:25.290 --> 00:11:28.280
to give me some flak,
especially little girls.

00:11:28.280 --> 00:11:31.240
And I was telling Kate
this story yesterday.

00:11:31.240 --> 00:11:37.620
At one school I was at, I probably
shouldn't have done this but I did,

00:11:37.620 --> 00:11:40.720
this little girl raised her hand
after my presentation and she said,

00:11:40.720 --> 00:11:43.580
"Are you ever going to write a book
with a girl as a main character?"

00:11:43.580 --> 00:11:46.190
And she kind of caught me off guard
and I didn't quite know what to say

00:11:46.190 --> 00:11:48.980
and I said, "Well, um, hmm, uh,

00:11:48.980 --> 00:11:52.240
well, uh, Mercy Watson's a girl."

00:11:52.240 --> 00:11:55.750
And the girl looked at me, I mean,
I think she almost put her hands

00:11:55.750 --> 00:11:59.110
on her hips and went
"Mercy Watson's a pig."

00:11:59.110 --> 00:12:01.870 position:56%
And I said, "Oh yeah, you're right."

00:12:01.870 --> 00:12:04.280
And the teacher helped me
out, she kind of stepped in.

00:12:04.280 --> 00:12:06.300
She said, "But technically, you
didn't write those books, right?"

00:12:06.300 --> 00:12:07.960
And I said, "Yes, that's right.

00:12:07.960 --> 00:12:09.880
I didn't write those books,"
which had kind of saved me.

00:12:09.880 --> 00:12:12.540
So this is the first
book with a girl.

00:12:12.540 --> 00:12:13.840
It didn't start that way.

00:12:13.840 --> 00:12:15.440
It actually started
like all my other books.

00:12:15.440 --> 00:12:19.000
It started with a boy, and it
started out as a rhyming book.

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:22.750
