00:24:37.060 --> 00:24:38.360
Wait, hold on.

00:24:38.360 --> 00:24:39.660
I'll get you next, yes.

00:24:39.660 --> 00:24:40.960
Yep?

00:24:40.960 --> 00:24:42.810
&gt;&gt; How did you get inspired
to write about a lake monster?

00:24:42.810 --> 00:24:48.360
You could've like written
about a tree monster or --

00:24:48.360 --> 00:24:49.660
&gt;&gt; Chris Van Dusen: Yeah!

00:24:49.660 --> 00:24:51.730
&gt;&gt; Or based it away from the lake.

00:24:51.730 --> 00:24:53.030
&gt;&gt; Chris Van Dusen:
That's a great question.

00:24:53.030 --> 00:24:56.450
The reason I wrote about a lake
monster is I live near a big lake

00:24:56.450 --> 00:24:57.750
in Maine.

00:24:57.750 --> 00:25:00.050
There's a big lake in my town.

00:25:00.050 --> 00:25:02.190
And it's a really deep lake
and I always sort of --

00:25:02.190 --> 00:25:04.470
it's the lake that's sort
of pictured in this book.

00:25:04.470 --> 00:25:08.550
And I've always sort of been
fascinated by lake monsters.

00:25:08.550 --> 00:25:11.340
When I was a kid, the Loch
Ness Monster was really popular

00:25:11.340 --> 00:25:14.360
and people were always finding new
pictures of the Loch Ness Monster.

00:25:14.360 --> 00:25:20.450
And so I've always been
fascinated by lake monsters.

00:25:20.450 --> 00:25:23.650
But originally I thought maybe the
monster would have a personality,

00:25:23.650 --> 00:25:25.660
the monster would talk,
too, and all that.

00:25:25.660 --> 00:25:28.610
But I decided to just abandon that
and just make the monster not talk

00:25:28.610 --> 00:25:32.120
and just become a great friend
to this very brave girl.

00:25:32.120 --> 00:25:36.290
And I think it's such a cool idea
to have like this huge friend.,

00:25:36.290 --> 00:25:37.590
you know, living in the lake

00:25:37.590 --> 00:25:39.120
that you could just
have so much fun with.

00:25:39.120 --> 00:25:40.420
That's a great question.

00:25:40.420 --> 00:25:42.030
We had a question right down here.

00:25:42.030 --> 00:25:43.330
&gt;&gt; I'm so sorry.

00:25:43.330 --> 00:25:45.130
&gt;&gt; Chris Van Dusen: That's okay.

00:25:45.130 --> 00:25:49.580
[ Inaudible Audience Question ]

00:25:49.580 --> 00:25:50.880
She said when you create a story,

00:25:50.880 --> 00:25:53.010
did the pictures come first
or the words come first?

00:25:53.010 --> 00:25:56.790
It kind of goes hand in hand when
you're working as an illustrator

00:25:56.790 --> 00:25:59.250
because a lot of times
when I'm writing the story,

00:25:59.250 --> 00:26:01.440
I do little thumbnail
sketches of what I sort

00:26:01.440 --> 00:26:03.510
of picture would be on each spread.

00:26:03.510 --> 00:26:06.910
But I really have to finish up
the story completely before I go

00:26:06.910 --> 00:26:10.750
to the series of tight
sketches and final art, so.

00:26:10.750 --> 00:26:13.690
We have one more question and
I think that's going to be it

00:26:13.690 --> 00:26:15.530
because I'm being told
to wrap it up.

00:26:15.530 --> 00:26:16.990
So, yes.

00:26:16.990 --> 00:26:20.480
&gt;&gt; How did you make the pictures?

00:26:20.480 --> 00:26:22.130
&gt;&gt; Chris Van Dusen: How
did I make the pictures?

00:26:22.130 --> 00:26:23.430
That's a great question.

00:26:23.430 --> 00:26:27.490
All my illustrations in all my
books are actually paintings.

00:26:27.490 --> 00:26:30.940
They're painted with a
paint called gouache,

00:26:30.940 --> 00:26:34.270
which some of you artists might
know, but kids always look at me

00:26:34.270 --> 00:26:36.370
and think I'm saying "squash."

00:26:36.370 --> 00:26:38.850
But it's actually gouache,
it's a water-based paint.

00:26:38.850 --> 00:26:42.850
It's like an opaque watercolor and
I usually start with a background

00:26:42.850 --> 00:26:44.150
and work to the foreground.

00:26:44.150 --> 00:26:45.650
Takes me about two weeks

00:26:45.650 --> 00:26:48.780
to do a typical spread
illustration for a book.

00:26:48.780 --> 00:26:53.670
So altogether, a book can take like
seven, eight, nine, ten months.

00:26:53.670 --> 00:26:55.770
The Circus Ship had
a lot of details,

00:26:55.770 --> 00:26:58.960
that took me about 14 months
to paint those pictures.

00:26:58.960 --> 00:27:01.630
I think we have to leave it there
because I don't want to bump

00:27:01.630 --> 00:27:04.510
in on Kate's time and I
know she's here and waiting.

00:27:04.510 --> 00:27:06.190
So thank you guys so much.

00:27:06.190 --> 00:27:07.490
I really enjoyed it.

00:27:07.490 --> 00:27:09.510
Have a great festival!

